The paper introduces a framework for efficient execution of iterative learning algorithms on massive and dense datasets using distributed computing machines. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper focuses on exploiting data structure to factorize it into an ensemble of lower rank subspaces, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also mentions the creation of sparse low-dimensional representations of the data, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) or Data Mining (cs.DM). Finally, the paper mentions the use of APIs for automated adoption of the framework, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI).
